    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Currency Converter</h2>
      <p>
        Our free currency converter supports 20 of the world's most widely traded currencies, including the US Dollar, Euro, British Pound, Japanese Yen, and more. Simply enter the amount you want to convert, select the source currency from the dropdown, and choose the target currency. The converter instantly displays the converted amount, the exchange rate used, and the inverse rate. You can also use the swap button to quickly reverse the conversion direction.
      </p>
      <p>
        Whether you are planning international travel, managing business transactions across borders, or simply curious about currency values, this tool provides a quick reference. Keep in mind that the rates shown are approximate static rates and should not be used for actual financial transactions. For live rates, consult your bank, a forex broker, or a dedicated rate service.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Currency Exchange Rates</h2>
      <p>
        Exchange rates represent the value of one currency relative to another. They are determined by the foreign exchange market, the largest financial market in the world with over $7.5 trillion in daily trading volume. Rates fluctuate constantly during trading hours based on supply and demand, which are influenced by economic data releases, central bank decisions, geopolitical events, and market sentiment.
      </p>

      <h3>Factors That Influence Exchange Rates</h3>
      <p>
        Interest rate differentials are one of the strongest drivers of exchange rates. When a country raises interest rates, its currency often strengthens because higher rates attract foreign investment. Inflation rates also play a key role, as countries with lower inflation tend to see their currencies appreciate over time. Trade balances, political stability, government debt levels, and economic growth all contribute to the complex dynamics of currency valuation.
      </p>

      <h3>Tips for Getting the Best Exchange Rate</h3>
      <p>
        When exchanging currency for travel or business, avoid airport and hotel exchange counters, which typically charge the widest spreads. Instead, use your bank or credit union, which usually offers better rates. Consider using a credit card with no foreign transaction fees for purchases abroad. For larger amounts, compare rates from multiple exchange services and negotiate. Online transfer services often offer more competitive rates than traditional banks for international wire transfers.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How does a currency converter work?</h3>
      <p>
        A currency converter uses exchange rates to calculate how much one currency is worth in another. It converts the source amount to a base currency (usually USD) and then converts from the base to the target currency. For example, to convert EUR to JPY, the tool first converts EUR to USD, then USD to JPY using the respective exchange rates.
      </p>

      <h3>Are these exchange rates live or real-time?</h3>
      <p>
        The exchange rates in this tool are approximate static rates and may not reflect current market values. For actual financial transactions, always check with your bank or a live exchange rate service for the most up-to-date rates. Exchange rates fluctuate constantly during trading hours based on global supply and demand.
      </p>

      <h3>What factors influence currency exchange rates?</h3>
      <p>
        Exchange rates are influenced by interest rate differentials between countries, inflation rates, political stability, economic performance (GDP, employment), trade balances, government debt levels, and market speculation. Central bank policies, particularly interest rate decisions, tend to have the most immediate impact on currency values.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the spread on currency exchange?</h3>
      <p>
        The spread is the difference between the buy (bid) and sell (ask) price of a currency pair. Banks and exchange services profit from this spread. Airport and hotel exchange services typically have the widest spreads (3-10%), while online forex brokers offer tighter spreads (0.01-1%). Always compare the total cost including spreads and fees before exchanging currency.
      </p>

      <h3>Which are the most traded currencies in the world?</h3>
      <p>
        The US Dollar (USD) is by far the most traded currency, involved in about 88% of all forex transactions. The Euro (EUR) is second at 31%, followed by the Japanese Yen (JPY) at 17%, British Pound (GBP) at 13%, and the Chinese Yuan (CNY) at 7%. These five currencies make up the vast majority of global foreign exchange volume.
      </p>
    

